Very good for winter afternoon tea or to cheer up winter-sad office staff. I prefer to cook less the cake to keep very moist inside. It is wonderfull with a hot spiced wine.

Rating: 3
An easy and unassuming cake for a delicious breakfast on a non-special occasion. It has a fluffy, light, moist texture, is low fat, and with the following modifications I would definately make it again. I had no applesauce so I substituted buttermilk, which worked great. Taking other reviewer's advice, I substituted maple syrup for 1/2 the brown sugar, and doubled the cinnamon. Everyone had only compliments.

Rating: 3
I just made this cake and it is light and delicious. I can definitely taste the maple, but if you prefer a deeper maple taste, try using Grade B maple syrup. I also used homemade applesauce that already had cinnamon in it. The house smells great while it's baking -- a very nice autumn dessert.

Rating: 3
I used walnut oil instead of vegetable and added a 1/2 cup dark raisins. Quite yummy and my husband liked it a lot, too.

